TrailerAdapter → TrailerNavigation → StreamResolver (NewPipe) → Video Overlay (View/Compose) → ExoPlayer
    (UI)            (Controller)          (Extractor)             (Player UI)        (Playback)



     DownloaderImpl:
     DownloaderImpl extends NewPipe’s Downloader and translates NewPipe “extractor requests” into real OkHttp calls.
     It also injects “more legit” headers (desktop Chrome UA, language, consent cookie, no-cache). If it detects rate-limit/captcha
     signals (HTTP 429 or “captcha” in body), it throws a ReCaptchaException so your extraction flow can fail fast instead of hanging.

     NewPipeExtractorViewer:
     1. Calls NewPipe.init(getDownloader()) in initialize() so NewPipe will use your DownloaderImpl for its extraction HTTP traffic.
     2. Inflates an overlay layout containing a Media3 PlayerView, positions it over your UI, hides it by default, and adds it to parentView so it can sit on top of Compose.
     3. On showTrailer(), it makes the overlay visible, brings it to front, and blocks focus from going back to Compose while the video is up.



     DownloaderImpl.kt:
     -  Persistent cookies (step 6): Added an in-file PersistentCookieJar that stores expiry-based cookies in SharedPreferences and reloads them on app restart.
        This helps with YouTube consent/session continuity so NewPipe extraction gets blocked less often.

     -  No static Cookie header: The interceptor does not inject any Cookie: header—cookies are managed by the jar (more realistic, fewer conflicts).

     -  Unified User-Agent + sane defaults: Ensures User-Agent, Accept-Language, Accept, and conservative cache headers are always present so extraction behaves consistently.

     -  More specific block/captcha detection: Replaced naive "captcha" substring checks with stronger signals: 429, /sorry/, consent.youtube.com, plus real
        recaptcha/unusual-traffic HTML markers (only when content-type is HTML).

     -  Response always closes (step 1): Changed network execution to execute().use { response -> ... } so the OkHttp Response is always closed (prevents
        leaks / connection pool exhaustion / “random hangs” after many requests).

     -  Exposes OkHttpClient: Added okHttpClient() so playback can reuse the same client (cookies/UA/redirect behavior) as extraction.


     NewPipeExtractorViewer.kt (View overlay):
     -  Removed reflection: Instead of Class.forName(...) to find OkHttpDataSource, it directly uses:
        OkHttpDataSource.Factory(getDownloader().okHttpClient())

     -  Playback matches extraction: ExoPlayer uses the same OkHttp client (and default headers) as NewPipe extraction → fewer cases where extraction works but playback 403’s.

     -  Correct Media3 wiring: Uses DefaultMediaSourceFactory(context).setDataSourceFactory(...) which is the reliable way in Media3 to apply your datasource factory.

     -  Everything else (layout inflate, sizing, focus blocking, key handling) stays basically the same, but now networking is consistent.


     HomeScreenTrailerVideoOverlayCompose.kt (Compose overlay):
     -  Removed reflection: Same change—uses OkHttpDataSource.Factory(...) directly.

     -  Fixed MediaSourceFactory creation: Uses DefaultMediaSourceFactory(context).setDataSourceFactory(...) so the datasource is actually used correctly
        (avoids subtle “still using default HTTP stack” issues).

     -  Key handling improvement: Stops swallowing every key (else -> false), so system/volume/etc. can bubble when appropriate.

     -  Keeps your existing flow: resolve URL via NewPipe, then play via ExoPlayer.